    <h1 class="article-title">Why Does Iron Rust? The Chemistry Behind Corrosion</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Explore the fascinating oxidation reaction that turns shiny iron into flaky rust, and discover why this process costs billions of dollars every year</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="video-wrapper">
    <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/YVKUMYlCw7w" title="The Chemistry of Rust - Periodic Videos" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">4Fe + 3O₂ + 6H₂O</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">4Fe(OH)₃</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">Every year, rusting costs the global economy over $2.5 trillion dollars. From bridges to cars, from ships to buildings, iron and steel structures are constantly battling against one of chemistry's most persistent reactions: oxidation. But what exactly happens when iron rusts, and why is this process so difficult to stop?</p>
  
  <p class="body-text">Rusting is a redox reaction where iron loses electrons (gets oxidized) while oxygen gains electrons (gets reduced). This process requires three key ingredients: iron, oxygen, and water. Without any one of these components, rust simply cannot form. The reaction occurs in several steps, starting with iron atoms losing electrons to form iron ions, which then combine with water and oxygen to create the familiar reddish-brown compound we call rust.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">What is Rust, Really?</div>
    <div class="callout-text">Rust isn't just one compound - it's actually a mixture of iron oxides and hydroxides, primarily Fe₂O₃·nH₂O (hydrated iron(III) oxide). The "n" represents a variable number of water molecules, which is why rust can have different colors and textures depending on environmental conditions.</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The rusting process is particularly destructive because rust occupies more volume than the original iron, causing it to flake off and expose fresh metal underneath. This creates a cycle where rusting continues until all the iron is consumed. Unlike some other metal oxides that form protective layers (like aluminum oxide), iron oxide is porous and doesn't protect the underlying metal. This is why prevention methods like galvanization (coating with zinc) or painting are so important - they create barriers that prevent oxygen and water from reaching the iron surface.</p>

